ok, Thailand", "@dptid": "125761544"}, "author": [{"ce:given-name": "Buravej", "preferred-name": {"ce:given-name": "Buravej", "ce:initials": "B.", "ce:surname": "Assavapongpaiboon", "ce:indexed-name": "Assavapongpaiboon B."}, "@seq": "2", "ce:initials": "B.", "@_fa": "true", "@type": "auth", "ce:surname": "Assavapongpaiboon", "@auid": "57194153037", "ce:indexed-name": "Assavapongpaiboon B."}]}, {"affiliation": {"@afid": "60022183", "affiliation-id": [{"@afid": "60022183", "@dptid": "100291259"}, {"@afid": "60028190"}], "ce:text": "Division of Nephrology, Department of Medicine, Faculty of Medicine, Chulalongkorn University and King Chulalongkorn Memorial Hospital, Bangkok, Thailand", "@dptid": "100291259"}, "author": [{"ce:given-name": "Paweena", "preferred-name": {"ce:given-name": "Paweena", "ce:initials": "P.", "ce:surname": "Susantitaphong", "ce:indexed-name": "Susantitaphong P."}, "@seq": "3", "ce:initials": "P.", "@_fa": "true", "@type": "auth", "ce:surname": "Susantitaphong", "@auid": "26025374300", "ce:indexed-name": "Susantitaphong P."}]}, {"affiliation": {"@afid": "60005558", "affiliation-id": {"@afid": "60005558", "@dptid": "113762882"}, "ce:text": "Division of Nephrology and Hypertension, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, MN, USA", "@dptid": "113762882"}, "author": [{"ce:given-name": "Wisit", "preferred-name": {"ce:given-name": "Wisit", "ce:initials": "W.", "ce:surname": "Cheungpasitporn", "ce:indexed-name": "Cheungpasitporn W."}, "@seq": "4", "ce:initials": "W.", "@_fa": "true", "@type": "auth", "ce:surname": "Cheungpasitporn", "@auid": "47160959700", "ce:indexed-name": "Cheungpasitporn W."}]}], "citation-title": "Non-alcoholic fatty liver disease as a risk factor for cholangiocarcinoma: a systematic review and meta-analysis", "abstracts": "BACKGROUND: Non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD) has been recently identified as a risk factor of gastrointestinal tract cancers, especially hepatocellular carcinoma, and colorectal cancer. Whether NAFLD is a risk factor for cholangiocarcinoma (CCA) remains inconclusive. The aim of this study is to determine a potential association between NAFLD and CCA, stratifying by its subtypes; intrahepatic CCA (iCCA), and extrahepatic CCA (eCCA).METHODS: A search was conducted for relevant studies published up to April 2017 using MEDLINE, EMBASE, Scopus and Cochrane databases. Odds ratio (OR) and adjusted OR with 95% confidence interval (CI) were estimated using a random-effects model. Subgroup analyses were conducted with study characteristics.RESULTS: Seven case-control studies were included in the analysis, with a total of 9,102 CCA patients (5,067 iCCA and 4,035 eCCA) and 129,111 controls. Overall, NAFLD was associated with an increased risk for CCA, with pooled OR of 1.95 (95%CI: 1.36-2.79, I 2 =76%). When classified by subtypes, NAFLD was associated with both iCCA and eCCA, with ORs of 2.22 (95%CI: 1.52-3.24, I 2 =67%) and 1.55 (95%CI: 1.03-2.33, I 2 =69%), respectively. The overall pooled adjusted ORs were 1.97 (95%CI: 1.41-2.75, I 2 =71%), 2.09 (95%CI, 1.49-2.91, I 2 =42%) and 2.05 (95%CI, 1.59-2.64, I 2 =0%) for all CCAs, iCCA, and eCCA, respectively.CONCLUSIONS: This meta-analysis suggests that NAFLD may potentially increase the risk of CCA development. The magnitude of NAFLD on CCA risk is greater for iCCA than eCCA subtype, suggestive of a common pathogenesis of iCCA and hepatocellular carcinoma. Further studies to confirm this association are warranted.TRIAL REGISTRATION: The protocol for this study was registered with PROSPERO (International Prospective Register of Systematic Reviews; no. CRD42016046573).", "citation-info": {"author-keywords": {"author-keyword": [{"$": "Bile duct cancer", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, {"$": "Cholangiocarcinoma", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, {"$": "NAFLD", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, {"$": "NASH", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, {"$": "Non-alcoholic fatty liver disease", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, {"$": "Non-alcoholic steatohepatitis", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, {"$": "Risk factor", "@xml:lang": "eng"}]}, "citation-type": {"@code": "ar"}, "citation-language": {"@language": "English", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, "abstract-language": {"@language": "English", "@xml:lang": "eng"}}, "source": {"sourcetitle-abbrev": "BMC Gastroenterol", "@country": "gbr", "translated-sourcetitle": {"$": "Medline", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, "issn": {"$": "1471230X", "@type": "electronic"}, "volisspag": {"voliss": {"@volume": "17", "@issue": "1"}, "pagerange": {"@first": "149"}}, "@type": "j", "publicationyear": {"@first": "2017"}, "sourcetitle": "BMC gastroenterology", "article-number": "149", "@srcid": "28251", "publicationdate": {"month": "12", "year": "2017", "date-text": {"@xfab-added": "true", "$": "8 December 2017"}, "day": "08"}}, "enhancement": {"classificationgroup": {"classifications": [{"@type": "ASJC", "classification": "2715"}, {"@type": "SUBJABBR", "classification": "MEDI"}]}}}, "item-info": {"copyright": {"$": "This record is sourced from MEDLINE/PubMed, a database of the U.S. National Library of Medicine", "@type": "Medline"}, "external-source": "MEDLINE", "dbcollection": [{"$": "MEDL"}, {"$": "Scopusbase"}], "history": {"date-created": {"@day": "24", "@timestamp": "BST 10:07:56", "@year": "2020", "@month": "07"}}, "itemidlist": {"itemid": [{"$": "622849231", "@idtype": "PUI"}, {"$": "911474576", "@idtype": "CAR-ID"}, {"$": "29216833", "@idtype": "MEDL"}, {"$": "85049262167", "@idtype": "SCP"}, {"$": "85049262167", "@idtype": "SGR"}], "ce:doi": "10.1186/s12876-017-0696-4"}}, "tail": null}}, "affiliation": [{"affiliation-city": "Bangkok", "@id": "60022183", "affilname": "King Chulalongkorn Memorial Hospital", "@href": "https://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60022183", "affiliation-country": "Thailand"}, {"affiliation-city": "Bangkok", "@id": "60002620", "affilname": "Faculty of Medicine, Chulalongkorn University", "@href": "https://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60002620", "affiliation-country": "Thailand"}, {"affiliation-city": "Rochester", "@id": "60005558", "affilname": "Mayo Clinic", "@href": "https://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60005558", "affiliation-country": "United States"}], "coredata": {"srctype": "j", "prism:issueIdentifier": "1", "eid": "2-s2.0-85049262167", "dc:description": "BACKGROUND: Non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD) has been recently identified as a risk factor of gastrointestinal tract cancers, especially hepatocellular carcinoma, and colorectal cancer. Whether NAFLD is a risk factor for cholangiocarcinoma (CCA) remains inconclusive. The aim of this study is to determine a potential association between NAFLD and CCA, stratifying by its subtypes; intrahepatic CCA (iCCA), and extrahepatic CCA (eCCA). METHODS: A search was conducted for relevant studies published up to April 2017 using MEDLINE, EMBASE, Scopus and Cochrane databases. Odds ratio (OR) and adjusted OR with 95% confidence interval (CI) were estimated using a random-effects model. Subgroup analyses were conducted with study characteristics. RESULTS: Seven case-control studies were included in the analysis, with a total of 9,102 CCA patients (5,067 iCCA and 4,035 eCCA) and 129,111 controls. Overall, NAFLD was associated with an increased risk for CCA, with pooled OR of 1.95 (95%CI: 1.36-2.79, I 2 =76%). When classified by subtypes, NAFLD was associated with both iCCA and eCCA, with ORs of 2.22 (95%CI: 1.52-3.24, I 2 =67%) and 1.55 (95%CI: 1.03-2.33, I 2 =69%), respectively. The overall pooled adjusted ORs were 1.97 (95%CI: 1.41-2.75, I 2 =71%), 2.09 (95%CI, 1.49-2.91, I 2 =42%) and 2.05 (95%CI, 1.59-2.64, I 2 =0%) for all CCAs, iCCA, and eCCA, respectively. CONCLUSIONS: This meta-analysis suggests that NAFLD may potentially increase the risk of CCA development. The magnitude of NAFLD on CCA risk is greater for iCCA than eCCA subtype, suggestive of a common pathogenesis of iCCA and hepatocellular carcinoma. Further studies to confirm this association are warranted. TRIAL REGISTRATION: The